<p><a name="The_Renaissance_and_Reformation" id="The_Renaissance_and_Reformation"></a></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Stained_glass&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: The Renaissance and Reformation">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">The Renaissance and Reformation</span></h3>
<p>In Europe, stained glass continued to be produced with the style evolving from the Gothic to the Classical style, which is widely represented in <a href="/wiki/Germany" title="Germany">Germany</a>, <a href="/wiki/Belgium" title="Belgium">Belgium</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Netherlands" title="Netherlands">Netherlands</a>, despite the rise of <a href="/wiki/Protestantism" title="Protestantism">Protestantism</a>. In <a href="/wiki/France" title="France">France</a>, much glass of this period was produced at the <a href="/wiki/Limoges" title="Limoges">Limoges</a> factory, and in Italy at <a href="/wiki/Murano" title="Murano">Murano</a>, where stained glass and faceted <a href="/wiki/Lead_crystal" title="Lead crystal" class="mw-redirect">lead crystal</a> are often coupled together in the same window. Ultimately, the French Revolution brought about the neglect or destruction of many windows in France. At the <a href="/wiki/English_Reformation" title="English Reformation">Reformation</a>, in England large numbers of Medieval and Renaissance windows windows were smashed and replaced with plain glass. The <a href="/wiki/Dissolution_of_the_Monasteries" title="Dissolution of the Monasteries">Dissolution of the Monasteries</a> under <a href="/wiki/Henry_VIII_of_England" title="Henry VIII of England">Henry VIII</a> and the injunctions of <a href="/wiki/Oliver_Cromwell" title="Oliver Cromwell">Oliver Cromwell</a> against "abused images" (the object of veneration) resulted in the loss of thousands of windows. Few remain undamaged; of them the windows in the private chapel at <a href="/wiki/Hengrave_Hall" title="Hengrave Hall">Hengrave Hall</a> in Suffolk are among the finest. With the latter wave of destruction the traditional methods of working with stained glass died and were not to be rediscovered in England until the early 19th century. See <a href="/wiki/Stained_glass_-_British_glass,_1811-1918" title="Stained glass - British glass, 1811-1918" class="mw-redirect">Stained glass - British glass, 1811-1918</a> for more details.</p>
