<p><a name="Revival_in_France" id="Revival_in_France"></a></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Stained_glass&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Revival in France">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Revival in France</span></h3>
<p>In France there was a greater continuity of stained glass production than in England. In the early 19th century most stained glass was made of large panes that were extensively painted and fired, the designs often being copied directly from oil paintings by famous artists. In 1824 the <a href="/wiki/Sevres" title="Sevres" class="mw-redirect">Sevres</a> Porcelain factory began producing stained glass to supply the increasing demand. In France many churches and cathedrals suffered despoilation during the <a href="/wiki/French_Revolution" title="French Revolution">French Revolution</a>. During the 19th century a great number of churches were restored by <a href="/wiki/Viollet-le-Duc" title="Viollet-le-Duc" class="mw-redirect">Viollet-le-Duc</a>. Many of France's finest ancient windows were restored at this time. From 1839 onwards much stained glass was produced that very closely imitates medieval glass, both in the artwork and in the nature of the glass itself. The pioneers were Henri Gèrente and Andre Lusson.<sup id="cite_ref-GC_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-GC-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> Other glass was designed in a more Classical manner, and characterised by the brilliant cerulean colour of the blue backgrounds (as against the purple-blue of the glass of Chartres) and the use of pink and mauve glass.</p>
<table class="gallery" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
<tr>
<td>
