<p><a name="Revival_in_Europe" id="Revival_in_Europe"></a></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Stained_glass&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Revival in Europe">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Revival in Europe</span></h3>
<p>During the mid to late 19th century, many of Germany's ancient buildings were restored, and some, such as <a href="/wiki/Cologne_Cathedral" title="Cologne Cathedral">Cologne Cathedral</a> were completed in the medieval style. There was a great demand for stained glass. The designs for many windows were based directly on the work of famous engravers such as <a href="/wiki/Albrecht_Durer" title="Albrecht Durer" class="mw-redirect">Albrecht Durer</a>. Original designs often imitate this style. Much 19th century German glass has large sections of painted detail rather than outlines and details dependent on the lead. The Royal Bavarian Glass painting Studio was founded by Ludwig I in 1827.<sup id="cite_ref-GC_1-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-GC-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> A major firm was Mayer of Munich which commenced glass production in 1860, and is still operating as <i>Franz Mayer of Munich, Inc.</i>. German stained glass found a market across Europe, in America and Australia. Stained glass studios were also founded in Italy and Belgium at this time.<sup id="cite_ref-GC_1-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-GC-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<table class="gallery" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
