<p><a name="Innovations_in_the_United_States" id="Innovations_in_the_United_States"></a></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Stained_glass&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Innovations in the United States">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Innovations in the United States</span></h3>
<div class="rellink noprint relarticle mainarticle">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Tiffany_glass" title="Tiffany glass">Tiffany glass</a></div>
<p>Notable American practitioners include <a href="/wiki/John_La_Farge" title="John La Farge" class="mw-redirect">John La Farge</a> (1835-1910) who invented opalescent glass and for which he received a US patent <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1880-02-24"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="02-24"><a href="/wiki/February_24" title="February 24">February 24</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1880" title="1880">1880</a></span>, and <a href="/wiki/Louis_Comfort_Tiffany" title="Louis Comfort Tiffany">Louis Comfort Tiffany</a> (1848-1933), who received several patents for variations of the same opalescent process in November of the same year and is believed to have invented the copper foil method as an alternative to lead, and used it extensively in windows, lamps and other decorations.</p>
<table class="gallery" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
<tr>
<td>
<div class="gallerybox" style="width: 155px;">
<div class="thumb" style="padding: 13px 0; width: 150px;">
<div style="margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; width: 120px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Girl_with_Cherry_Blossoms_-_Tiffany_Glass_%26_Decorating_Company,_c._1890.JPG" class="image" title="Girl with Cherry Blossoms - Tiffany Glass &amp; Decorating Company, c. 1890.JPG"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Girl_with_Cherry_Blossoms_-_Tiffany_Glass_%26_Decorating_Company%2C_c._1890.JPG/90px-Girl_with_Cherry_Blossoms_-_Tiffany_Glass_%26_Decorating_Company%2C_c._1890.JPG" width="90" height="120" border="0" /></a></div>
</div>
<div class="gallerytext">
<p>Many of the distinctive types of glass invented by Tiffany are demonstrated within this single small panel including "fracture-streamer glass" and "drapery glass".</p>
</div>
</div>
</td>
<td>
<div class="gallerybox" style="width: 155px;">
